@node FAQ.Monitors.5.01 "Monitors Questions"
@toc FAQ.Monitors

    5.01 What types of monitors are there?

            There are too many types of monitors available to go into
        detail on them all. Basically, the Amiga can use almost all of
        them provided that the Amiga has the proper port and the proper
        cable.


            1. RGB is the most common type of monitor used for Amigas.
               Every Amiga has a 23 PIN RGB port capable of outputting
               interlaced video modes. This provides a nice sharp
               display for all of the early Amiga computers.

            2. COMPOSITE is used mainly by video producers, often in
               conjunction with another monitor. Although this is a
               very inexpensive monitor which is very easy to find,
               the colors tend to bleed like a television, making it
               harder to use where color and sharpness is important.
               Many Amigas offer a color or monochrome Composite video
               output.

            3. TELEVISION is also used by many people to substitute as
               a Composite monitor. The advantage is that televisions
               are extremely common, and work well for video users.
               Another common use is for new owners who cannot afford
               more than just the Amiga itself.

            4. DIGITAL monitors have a nice picture quality, but may be
               limited in the number of colors they can display. A
               special cable is necessary to connect to a Digital
               monitor, and this type of monitor is not suggested.

            5. VGA monitors are used by all the high end Amigas. These
               support flicker-free displays for many machines, along
               with sharp colors without smearing.

            6. SVGA monitors, like VGA, also offer higher resolutions
               and higher persistance for interlaced and flickering
               display modes. These are most common on the high end
               Amigas.

            7. MULTISCAN monitors are capable of displaying all screenmodes
               supported by the Amiga, which the SVGA and VGA monitors
               cannot produce. Any user who uses the wide variety of
               display modes should invest in a Multiscan or
               MultiFrequency monitor.


@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Monitors.5.02 "Monitors Questions"
@toc FAQ.Monitors

